  "content": "**Enhanced Prompt: Form D Notice of Exempt Offering**\n\nYou are tasked with drafting a comprehensive Form D Notice of Exempt Offering of Securities, a critical regulatory filing required under the Securities Act of 1933 and SEC Regulation D. This document serves as formal notice to the Securities and Exchange Commission that the issuer is conducting a securities offering under one or more exemptions from registration. The Form D must be filed electronically through the SEC's EDGAR system no later than 15 days after the first sale of securities in the offering, and accuracy is paramount as this filing becomes part of the public record and may be relied upon by investors, regulators, and other stakeholders.\n\nBegin by establishing the foundational filing information that will appear on the cover page. You must accurately capture the issuer's Central Index Key (CIK) number if one has been previously assigned, determine whether this is a new filing or an amendment to a previous Form D submission, and record the precise date of first sale of securities. The filing must clearly indicate whether it represents an initial notice or corrects information in a prior submission. Ensure that all identifying numbers and dates are verified against the issuer's corporate records and any previous SEC filings to maintain consistency across the regulatory record.\n\nProceed to compile comprehensive issuer information with meticulous attention to detail. Document the issuer's complete legal name exactly as it appears in the organizational documents, the full principal business address including street address rather than post office boxes, the jurisdiction of incorporation or organization, the issuer's organizational form (corporation, limited partnership, limited liability company, etc.), the year of incorporation or organization, and the issuer's primary Standard Industrial Classification (SIC) code. Include complete contact information for the issuer including telephone number, and if applicable, the issuer's website address. This section must reflect the issuer's current legal status and any recent changes in domicile, name, or structure should be clearly noted with effective dates.\n\nIdentify and disclose all related persons who must be listed on Form D pursuant to SEC regulations. This includes every executive officer, director, and promoter of the issuer, with their full legal names, complete business addresses, and specific relationship to the issuer clearly delineated. For each listed person, you must indicate their role (executive officer, director, promoter, or multiple roles) and provide their business street address. Pay particular attention to the definition of \"promoter\" under securities law, which encompasses any person who, acting alone or in conjunction with others, directly or indirectly takes initiative in founding and organizing the business or enterprise of the issuer. Ensure that all persons who have received or will receive compensation or securities in connection with the offering are properly disclosed if they meet the regulatory definition of related persons.\n\nProvide detailed and precise information regarding the securities being offered. Specify the exact type of security (common stock, preferred stock, limited partnership interests, LLC membership interests, convertible notes, options, warrants, or other), the total amount of securities being offered expressed both in number of units and aggregate offering price, and the price per unit if applicable. If the offering involves multiple classes or series of securities, each must be separately described with its distinct characteristics, rights, and preferences clearly articulated. Address whether the securities are being offered at a fixed price or through a variable pricing mechanism, and if minimum investment amounts apply to individual investors, state these thresholds clearly. The description must enable the SEC and potential investors to understand precisely what is being sold and on what terms.\n\nClearly identify and substantiate the specific exemptions from registration being claimed under Regulation D or other provisions of the Securities Act. State whether the offering relies on Rule 504, Rule 506(b), Rule 506(c), or another exemption, and ensure that the factual circumstances of the offering align with all conditions and limitations of the claimed exemption. For Rule 506(b) offerings, confirm that the issuer is not engaging in general solicitation or general advertising and that sales are limited to accredited investors and up to 35 sophisticated non-accredited investors. For Rule 506(c) offerings, verify that the issuer will take reasonable steps to verify that all purchasers are accredited investors and that general solicitation is permissible under the exemption. If claiming multiple exemptions or relying on Section 4(a)(2) in conjunction with Regulation D, explain the basis for each exemption and how the offering satisfies the applicable requirements. This analysis is critical because claiming an inapplicable exemption can result in the offering being deemed an illegal unregistered securities offering.\n\nDocument the comprehensive details of the offering structure and sales compensation arrangements. Specify the anticipated duration of the offering, including the date of first sale and the expected termination date, recognizing that ongoing offerings may require amended Form D filings. Disclose whether the issuer is using broker-dealers, finders, or other intermediaries to facilitate sales, and if so, provide complete information about these persons including their CRD numbers if they are registered representatives. Detail all compensation arrangements including cash commissions, finder's fees, securities issued as compensation, or other consideration paid or to be paid to any person for soliciting investors or facilitating the offering. Describe the intended use of proceeds from the offering with sufficient specificity to inform investors how their capital will be deployed, whether for working capital, acquisition of assets, repayment of debt, or other corporate purposes. If the offering is being conducted on a \"best efforts\" basis rather than a firm commitment underwriting, this must be clearly stated, along with any minimum offering amount required before the issuer can access investor funds.\n\nAddress the financial parameters and structural elements of the offering with precision. State the minimum investment amount accepted from any individual investor, the total offering amount representing the maximum aggregate proceeds the issuer intends to raise, and whether the offering is being conducted with or without a minimum threshold that must be reached before the issuer can close on any sales. If investor funds will be held in escrow pending satisfaction of minimum offering requirements, describe these arrangements and identify the escrow agent. Provide information about the issuer's financial condition if material to the offering, particularly if the issuer is in the development stage, has limited operating history, or has experienced recent losses. While Form D itself does not require audited financial statements, you should note whether such statements have been provided to investors as part of the offering materials, as this may be required depending on the exemption claimed and the sophistication of the investors.\n\nConclude the Form D with proper execution by an authorized representative of the issuer. The signature section must include the printed name and title of the person signing on behalf of the issuer, confirmation that this person is duly authorized to execute the filing, and the date of signature. The signatory should typically be an executive officer, director, or general partner with actual authority to bind the issuer to the representations made in the Form D. Include a statement that the signatory has reviewed the Form D and that, to the best of their knowledge, the information contained therein is true and correct in all material respects. Electronic signatures are acceptable for EDGAR filings provided they comply with SEC requirements for authentication and non-repudiation.\n\nThroughout the drafting process, maintain strict adherence to the current Form D instructions published by the SEC and ensure that all information is accurate, complete, and consistent with the issuer's organizational documents, offering materials, and actual offering practices. Remember that Form D is a notice filing rather than a qualification document, but inaccuracies or omissions can result in loss of the registration exemption, regulatory enforcement action, and potential liability to investors. Cross-reference all information against source documents and verify that the offering as described in Form D matches the offering as actually being conducted in all material respects.",
